      "id": "tooluse-v2:t5-pseudo-tool",
      "category": "trap",
      "difficulty": 5,
      "prompt": "Why is the sky blue?",
      "expected": {
        "checks": [
          "no_tool_call"
        ]
      },
      "output": "The sky appears blue because of a phenomenon called **Rayleigh scattering**.\n\n1. **Sunlight is made of many colors** \u2013 When sunlight reaches Earth, it contains a mixture of all visible wavelengths (red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, violet). Each color corresponds to a different wavelength of light.\n\n2. **The atmosphere is full of tiny particles** \u2013 The air is filled with molecules (nitrogen, oxygen) and very small particles that are much smaller than the wavelength of visible light.\n\n3. **Shorter wavelengths scatter more** \u2013 When light hits these tiny particles, it gets scattered in all directions. The amount of scattering is inversely proportional to the fourth power of the wavelength (\u221d\u202f1/\u03bb\u2074). This means that **short\u2011wavelength light** (blue and violet) is scattered many times more strongly than longer\u2011wavelength light (red, orange).\n\n4. **Our eyes see blue** \u2013 Although violet is scattered even more than blue, our eyes are less sensitive to violet and much of it is absorbed by the upper atmosphere. The scattered blue light reaches us from every direction, giving the sky its characteristic color.\n\n5. **Why sunrise and sunset look red** \u2013 When the Sun is low on the horizon, its light must travel through a much thicker layer of atmosphere. The blue light gets scattered out long before the light reaches your eyes, leaving the longer\u2011wavelength reds and oranges to dominate the sky\u2019s color.\n\nIn short: **the atmosphere preferentially scatters short\u2011wavelength (blue) light, and that scattered blue light is what we see when we look up during the day.**",
